label chapter15:

    # [Scene: Greenline Reclamation Hub | Morning]

    scene bg ch15_5195df_1 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The steady beat of drills and the soft slap of boards being laid; distant gulls; a chorus of laughter and shouted instructions.]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Bright, driving strings with a steady percussion undercurrent—urgent, celebratory.]
    "You arrive to a hub that smells of wet earth and varnish, of salt and fresh-cut wood. The place hums like a heart restarted: tents for seedlings, splashy murals with hand-lettered slogans, and a line of hand-painted signs that insist, cheerfully, that this coast belongs to people, not profit."
    "Lina Park waves you over, her braid flaring with motion. Her hands are knuckled with soil; she passes you a pair of gloves with the fierce generosity of someone who has spent months teaching others how to hold the shore."
    show lina_park at left:
        zoom 0.7

    lina_park "About time you showed up, scientist-in-residence. We saved the best hole for your planting."
    show maya_calder at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_calder "You mean the part where I inevitably over-plan and someone yanks the schematic right out of my hands?"

    lina_park "Promise we only yank for practical reasons. Mostly for planting. Also, the kids from the school want to see the compass."
    "You feel the brass at your sternum even before you reach for it—the compass a familiar weight beneath your jacket. It steadies you like a name whispered in a roomful of strangers who are suddenly family."
    show mayor_amara_sol at center:
        zoom 0.7

    mayor_amara_sol "Federal funds will cover immediate relocations where necessary. Local oversight will govern the trust. Greenline expands today because we insisted it be accountable, not because money came on its own terms."
    hide lina_park
    show serena_voss at left:
        zoom 0.7

    serena_voss "We were reckless in the past. We are not the ones who will decide what remains. If I failed the town, I intend to help stitch it back."
    "There is friction between them still—legal teams, boardroom scars—but the friction now sparks rather than grinds: the kind that polishes something into usefulness."
    "Tomas Reyes arrives lugging a crate of oyster shells for the living shoreline terraces, his hands salt-washed and sure. He eyes you with the same practical tenderness he always has, like someone cataloguing whether the net can be mended."

    "Tomas Reyes" "You remember where your father used to tie the oldest marker? We planted there. Thought he'd like knowing we didn't leave it to rot."

    maya_calder "I—"
    "Your throat tightens in an old, private registry of things you can't yet say."

    maya_calder "—thank you. For keeping an eye on the memory."
    "Lina nudges you toward a shallow trench where saplings wait. The volunteers—students, fishermen, retired carpenters—move in a quick, bright choreography: root, tamp, water, celebrate. The work is noisy and precise; each action is a sentence in a speech no one wrote down but everyone now understands."

    menu:
        "Roll up your sleeves and plant the first sapling":
            "You plunge your hands into mud that smells like promise and old tides. Hands learning the new grammar of shore-making. Someone snaps a photo; Lina cheers loudly."
        "Stand back and talk logistics with Mayor Sol":
            "You pull out the notebook, eyes finding the new oversight charter. Amara reads the clauses aloud; her voice is steady and, for once, you let the practical words be a kind of comfort."

    # --- merge ---
    "Whatever decision you made, the hub moves forward. There is no single savior gesture here, only an accumulation of careful acts: legal language signed, a table established for community oversight, Serena's firm wired into the trust but answerable to town-elected stewards."
    hide maya_calder
    hide mayor_amara_sol
    hide serena_voss

    scene bg ch15_5195df_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A full, ecstatic cheer from someone who plants poorly and gets applause anyway.]
    # [Scene: New Boardwalk | Midday]

    scene bg ch15_5195df_3 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Folk instruments tuned into a celebratory cadence; children's voices, the clack of wooden boards; the slap of tide against pilings.]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Strings swell; brass flares—exhilaration tempered by tenderness.]
    "Elias Rowe is there, sleeves rolled, sketchbook open, hands smudged with charcoal and paint. He looks up when you approach, amber eyes catching the sun like a held promise."
    show elias_rowe at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_rowe "You found time to come see the chaos you started."
    show maya_calder at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_calder "I didn't start it. Everyone did."

    maya_calder "I mean it—every person here is part of the starts."

    elias_rowe "Still—there's a line you drew at the lab that made all this make sense. You held the blueprints in one hand and everyone's fear in the other. I don't know how you didn't drop either."
    "You tell him you almost did—every night for months—but then you remember the nervous, steady work of others, and your voice steadies like a tide finding a rhythm."

    maya_calder "I kept the numbers honest because I couldn't bear another lie. I kept coming because—"
    "You look at the boardwalk, at the families weaving between planters."

    maya_calder "—because this is who we are."
    "Elias Rowe reaches out, fingers brushing the corner of your Moleskine where it peeks from beneath your jacket. He doesn't pull it away; he simply holds the edge like a benediction."

    elias_rowe "You don't have to carry it alone anymore. Not unless you want to."
    "Maya Calder: (a pause, a rustle of breath) 'I don't know how to ask for help without feeling like I'm losing my north.'"

    elias_rowe "Asking isn't losing. It's calibrating. And calibration is part of what you do best."
    "His words are not grand. They are exact, patient tools, and for the first time in a long time you set the compass on the picnic table and leave it there—face-up, its brass catching the sun."

    menu:
        "Trace your father's initials on the compass rim":
            "Your fingertip finds the worn dent where your father once smoothed the metal. A private punctuation: grief acknowledged, not hidden."
        "Leave the compass on the table and let Elias fold his hand over yours":
            "Elias's palm is warm and callused. The contact is small and seismic. Around you, the crowd hums and the sea keeps time."

    # --- merge ---
    "You choose—some small, honest thing—and the world rearranges itself with astonishing tenderness. Elias does not demand a promise; he offers presence. You test the reach of that presence and find it answers."

    elias_rowe "Stay a little longer tonight? Help me mark out the next terrace lines? Or—"

    elias_rowe "—we could make dinner out of whatever the field kitchen has left."

    maya_calder "I'd like that. I want to see how the planting reads from the waterline. And then dinner. Especially if Lina's been hoarding cookies again."
    "A ripple of laughter passes between you, a thing both ordinary and miraculous. Around you, officials sign documents, volunteers exchange stories about lost markers and found saplings, and a press photographer snaps a dozen pictures that will make the papers tomorrow—pictures labeled 'Aster's Reach Rebuilds'."
    # [Scene: Old Breakwater | Dusk]
    hide elias_rowe
    hide maya_calder

    scene bg ch15_5195df_4 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The surf softens from roar to whisper; the creak of rope; a distant chorus of frogs and the delighted squeal of children exploring new tide pools.]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Gentle piano over a sustained, euphoric string pad—closure and forward motion braided.]
    "You walk the breakwater with Elias Rowe at your side and Tomas Reyes lagging behind, telling a story he has told a hundred times but never with this punch of triumph—the telling is part accounting and part prayer."

    "Tomas Reyes" "Remember the night that storm took the south pier? Thought we'd never get that smell of sea-rope back. Now look—kids are catching minnows where we almost lost the dock. Funny, ain't it? How the world's got patience if you give it a little patience back."
    show maya_calder at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_calder "It's not just patience. It's insistence, too. People insisted this coast was worth more than a ledger entry."
    "Mayor Amara Sol appears with Serena Voss close behind, both holding thermoses. The mayor hands you one without fuss; Serena Voss offers a small, almost apologetic nod and then, in a move that surprises even herself,"
    "traces her thumb over the locket at her throat and lifts her chin as though committing."
    show mayor_amara_sol at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mayor_amara_sol "A cooperative trust, legal oversight, federal grants, community co-management—none of this was inevitable. It happened because people argued until they couldn't help but find ways to build together."
    show serena_voss at center:
        zoom 0.7

    serena_voss "I lost a lot of illusions about the fastest fix. I don't regret moving resources—only regret if I moved them without the town's voice. I'll answer for that. Publicly. Privately. In the best ways I can."
    "Her words are not absolution; they are labor. You accept them without granting absolution—because healing is a process and this—the trust, the wetlands, the community board—is the work of that process."
    "Elias Rowe stops at the picnic table where the compass rests between two mugs. He reaches for your hand. The gesture is unornamented and absolute—a small clasp that contains an entire, complicated history: your father's tide"
    "lines, your long nights alone at the lab, Elias's sketches folded into plans that have become people-shaped things, and the town's bruised, brilliant determination."
    hide maya_calder
    show elias_rowe at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_rowe "So—this is us, then? Not perfect. Messy. Loud. Maybe glorious."
    hide mayor_amara_sol
    show maya_calder at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_calder "This is us. And I will still measure. I will still grieve. But I won't be alone while I do it."
    "His fingers tighten once, the press of skin and shared warmth. Around you, the town moves—the Mayor gesturing to a new oversight board, Lina corralling teenagers into a celebratory march, Tomas balancing a sapling with ceremonial gravity—tiny rituals that stitch the past and the future together."
    hide serena_voss
    hide elias_rowe
    hide maya_calder

    scene bg ch15_5195df_5 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A swell of applause from the boardwalk; a child's laugh like a bell; waves confirming their ancient metronome.]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Climactic, fervent strings resolving into a single sustained note that lingers like a vow.]
    "You let the feeling settle—cautious, fierce, and very, very bright. There are consequences ahead: legal audits, maintenance demands, hard conversations about who moves and who stays. The work will not end. The sea will keep remembering"
    "storms and old lines and buried anchors. But you also feel—deep in the smooth of your hand where it rests in Elias Rowe's—that you are held. That asking for help did not dissolve you into weakness;"
    "it multiplied what you could do."
    "Serena Voss steps forward, unexpectedly earnest."
    show serena_voss at left:
        zoom 0.7

    serena_voss "We will fund the next five years with strict public accounting. We'll train local teams to maintain the living shorelines. We will not let a single decision be made without the town's representatives. I will be held to that."
    show maya_calder at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_calder "And you'll sit on the oversight board?"

    serena_voss "If the town will have me. To be held is a new thing for me. I'm ready for the accountability."
    "There is no theatrical absolution. There's the harder thing—acceptance of oversight, a publicly recorded intent, and the start of work that will be measured in seasons, not headlines."
    "Elias Rowe squeezes your hand once more, a small anchor."
    show elias_rowe at center:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_rowe "Whatever comes next—I'll be here. Not to fix everything, but to be here."

    maya_calder "And I will let you be."
    "You turn your face to the sea. The light collapses into silver veins across the water. Far off, the Old Breakwater's silhouette breathes easier now—its scar turned into a living thing that will buffer storms and hold memories in marsh grass and mussel beds."
    "You sit at the picnic table, the compass between you like a small treaty. For a moment everything is noise: the town's voices, the slap of water, the music bundling into the dusk—but underpinning it all is a steady, incandescent peace."
    "You will still work. You will still measure. You will still grieve. But you will not do those things alone."
    hide serena_voss
    hide maya_calder
    hide elias_rowe

    scene bg ch15_5195df_6 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The mingled chorus of neighbors, sea, and a repaired town at work.]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A final, soaring resolution—strings, light percussion, a single, wordless chorus—that holds long enough to let the heart set.]
    "You rest your palm over the brass compass. Elias Rowe lays his hand over yours. The contact is simple, ordinary, and definitive."

    scene bg ch15_5195df_7 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Gentle decrescendo to a single warm chord. Fade out.]

    scene bg ch15_5195df_8 at full_bg
    "THE END"
    # [GAME END]
